**Background Image Setup:**
```css
body {
    background-image: url('my-background.jpg');
    background-position: center;
    background-size: cover;
    background-repeat: no-repeat;
    background-attachment: fixed;
}
```

**Background Size Options:**
```css
.cover {
    background-size: cover; /* Fits screen, may crop */
}

.contain {
    background-size: contain; /* Fits entire image */
}

.specific-size {
    background-size: 800px 600px;
}

.percentage {
    background-size: 100% 100%;
}
```

**Key Properties:**
- `background-position: center` - Keeps image centered
- `background-size: cover` - Makes image fit screen
- `background-repeat: no-repeat` - Prevents tiling
- `background-attachment: fixed` - Keeps background in place during scroll
- Gradients don't repeat by default

**CamelCase Format:**
- Start with lowercase letter
- Capitalize first letter of each new word
- No spaces or underscores

**Example:**
```javascript
var firstName = "John";
var lastName = "Doe";
var myAge = 25;
var userEmailAddress = "john@example.com";

function calculateTotalPrice() {
    // code here
}

function getUserData() {
    // code here
}
```

**Why use camelCase:**
- Standard convention in JavaScript
- Easy to read without spaces
- Distinguishes variables (camelCase) from constants (UPPER_CASE)
- Distinguishes from classes (PascalCase)

**Basic Switch:**
```javascript
switch (val) {
    case 1:
        answer = "alpha";
        break;
    case 2:
        answer = "beta";
        break;
    default:
        answer = "unknown";
}
```

**Multiple Cases:**
```javascript
switch (val) {
    case 1:
    case 2:
    case 3:
        answer = "low";
        break;
    case 4:
    case 5:
    case 6:
        answer = "medium";
        break;
    default:
        answer = "unknown";
}
```

**Key points:**
- `case` tests specific value
- `break` stops execution
- `default` runs if no match
- Without `break`, execution falls through

**Parameters vs Arguments:**
- **Parameters:** Placeholders in function definition
- **Arguments:** Values passed when calling function

**Example:**
```javascript
// Parameters: x, y
function add(x, y) {
    return x + y;
}

// Arguments: 2, 3
add(2, 3);  // Returns 5
```

**Default Parameters:**
```javascript
function greet(name = "Guest") {
    return `Hello, ${name}!`;
}

greet();       // "Hello, Guest!"
greet("Alice"); // "Hello, Alice!"
```

**Key points:**
- Order matters in both definition and calling
- Defaults used when argument is undefined
- Defaults can be expressions

**Basic Border Properties:**
```css
.box {
    border-width: 3px;
    border-color: red;
    border-style: solid;
    border-radius: 10px;
    padding: 20px;
}

/* Shorthand */
.box2 {
    border: 2px dashed blue;
    border-radius: 5px;
    padding: 15px;
}
```

**Common Border Styles:**
- `solid` - solid line
- `dashed` - dashed line
- `dotted` - dotted line
- `double` - double line
- `ridge` - 3D ridged border
- `groove` - 3D grooved border
- `inset` - 3D inset border
- `outset` - 3D outset border

**Individual Border Sides:**
```css
h1 {
    border-top-style: solid;
    border-bottom-style: dashed;
    border-left-style: dotted;
    border-right-style: double;
}

.box {
    border-top-width: 5px;
    border-bottom-width: 3px;
    border-left-width: 2px;
    border-right-width: 4px;

    border-top-color: red;
    border-bottom-color: blue;
    border-left-color: green;
    border-right-color: yellow;
}

/* Shorthand for individual sides */
.asymmetric {
    border-top: 8px solid purple;
    border-bottom: 2px dashed orange;
    border-left: 6px dotted teal;
    border-right: 4px ridge pink;
    padding: 20px;
}
```

getElementById() directly matches an element's ID without requiring a # symbol, while querySelector() uses CSS selector syntax and requires the # prefix.

Examples:

getElementById - no # symbol needed
document.getElementById('header');

querySelector - requires # symbol
document.querySelector('#header');

Both return array-like structures that you access using square brackets [] with an index. getElementsByClassName() returns an HTMLCollection, while querySelectorAll() returns a NodeList.

Examples:

getElementsByClassName returns HTMLCollection
const items = document.getElementsByClassName('menu-item');
items[0].style.color = 'blue';

querySelectorAll returns NodeList
const list = document.querySelectorAll('li');
list[2].style.fontWeight = 'bold';

The return statement exits the entire function immediately when executed, which stops the loop after just one iteration.

To apply changes to all items in a loop, use only statements without return:

// Wrong - stops after first iteration
for (let i = 0; i < choice.length; i++) {
    return (choice[i].style.color = 'red');
}

// Correct - processes all items
for (let i = 0; i < choice.length; i++) {
    choice[i].style.color = 'red';
}

Reading attributes: const title = document.querySelector('#mainHeading'); console.log(title.getAttribute('id'));

Setting or modifying an attribute: element.setAttribute('type', 'button');

Removing an attribute: element.removeAttribute('type');

Setting ID directly: element.id = 'myButton'; console.log(element.id);

Setting ID with setAttribute: element.setAttribute('id', 'myButton');

Use the classList property which provides methods to control CSS classes:

const newDiv = document.createElement('div');

Add a class: newDiv.classList.add('choice');

Remove a class: newDiv.classList.remove('choice');

Check if a class exists (returns true or false): console.log(newDiv.classList.contains('choice'));

Parent node traversal allows you to navigate up the DOM tree from a child element to its ancestors. Both parentNode and parentElement move up one level in the hierarchy, and you can chain them to go multiple levels up:

let div = document.querySelector('.choice');

Both navigate up 4 levels to ancestor elements
console.log(div.parentNode.parentNode.parentNode.parentNode);
console.log(div.parentElement.parentElement.parentElement.parentElement);

In most cases, parentNode and parentElement work the same way for HTML elements.

childNodes returns a NodeList that includes all types of nodes: element nodes, text nodes (spaces, newlines), and comment nodes. If you try to access .style on a text node, you get an error because text nodes don't have a .style property.

Solution: Use .children instead of .childNodes because .children only returns element nodes that have a .style property:

// Wrong - might access a text node
div.childNodes[2].style.backgroundColor = 'blue'; // Error!

// Correct - only element nodes
console.log(div.children);
div.children[1].style.backgroundColor = 'blue';

Select the element, define a function, and attach it using addEventListener():

const btn2 = document.querySelector('.btn2');

function alertbtn() {
    alert('BRUDAHHH');
}

Pass function name without () - don't call it immediately
btn2.addEventListener('click', alertbtn);

Important: Pass the function name without parentheses (alertbtn, not alertbtn()) so it executes when clicked, not immediately when the code runs.

Use classList.toggle() or check if a class exists, then add/remove it:

const revealBtn = document.querySelector('.reveal-center');
const hiddenContent = document.querySelector('.hidden-content');

function revealBot() {
    if (hiddenContent.classList.contains('revealBtn')) {
        hiddenContent.classList.remove('revealBtn');
    } else {
        hiddenContent.classList.add('revealBtn');
    }
}

revealBtn.addEventListener('click', revealBot);

CSS:
hidden-content { display: none; }
hidden-content.revealBtn { display: block; }

Event delegation means putting a single event listener on a parent element to handle events for many child elements, even children added later, by checking what was actually clicked using event bubbling.

Example with delegation:
document.querySelector('.items').addEventListener('click', function(e) {
    console.log(e.target.getAttribute('class') + ' is clicked');
});

Why it's useful: One parent, one listener handles all children. Perfect for lists, tables, and menus with similar elements. Note: e contains details about the click, and e.target is the element that was clicked.

.matches(selector) checks if an element fits a given CSS selector (tag, class, or id). It returns true or false:

document.querySelector('.items').addEventListener('click', function(e) {
    if (e.target.matches('button')) {
        e.target.style.backgroundColor = 'blue';
    }
    if (e.target.matches('#btn1')) {
        alert('Button 1 clicked!');
    }
    if (e.target.matches('.special')) {
        e.target.style.fontWeight = 'bold';
    }
});

Summary: .matches() asks 'does this thing fit the criteria?'
